 Ireland and Britain."],"variants":[{"name":"Delaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Cormac, Clancy, Colm, Conley, Conor, Dermot, Donal, Eamon, Eamonn, Finbar.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Laney   with fused preposition <i>de</i>.","Irish: Anglicized form, influenced by the Norman name, of Gaelic <b>Ó Dubhshláine</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dubhshláine</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>slán</i> ‘challenge, defiance’. MacLysaght, however, suggests that this element may be from the Sláinge river."]}]},{"name":"Rebecca","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, from the Latin form of the Hebrew name <i>Rebekah</i>, borne by the wife of Isaac, who was the mother of Esau and Jacob (Genesis 24–27). The Hebrew root occurs in the Bible only in the vocabulary word <i>marbek</i> ‘cattle stall’, and its connection with the name is doubtful. In any case, Rebecca was Aramean, and the name probably has a source in Aramaic. It has always been common as a Jewish name; in England and elsewhere it began to be used also by Christians from the 14th century onwards and especially at the time of the Reformation, when Old Testament names became popular. It was very common among the Puritans in the 17th century, and has enjoyed a tremendous vogue in England since the latter part of the 20th century, among people of many different creeds. In Scotland this is found as an Anglicized form of Beathag ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rebecca Dulaney was born in 1435, in Oxford, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Walter Dulany, was 20 and her mother, Susanna Dulaney, was 20. She married Thomas Henry Edson before 1455. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1529, at the age of 94."},"et":{"1435–1529":"1435–1529","1425–1455":"1425–1455","1475–1517":"1475–1517","1415–1436":"1415–1436","141